Since my city went into lockdown again and closed the gyms, I have been missing that Prana I get from lifting weights at the gym. Revolution has been a great alternative because I am pushed past my physical comfort limits with all the strength focus in this series, but I do so in a calming, freeing headspace that comes with doing Adrienes yoga. It is a great feeling to marry the two right now while trying to remain okay during the overwhelm of pandemic and lockdown.

I grew up in "power through" NYC and the whole idea of slowing down is so foreign to me. In the back of my head, I am like, "No way, I got to go fast!" But then I listen to Adriene and tell myself to trust and wowzers - it is exactly what I need. Energetically, physically, and emotionally. Thank you for sharing your gifts, Adriene

Adriene, one of the things I love most about following your yoga videos is the way you always encourage people to work at their own pace, find what feels good in their own bodies, and to experiment and play with the poses.  In the past in other yoga classes I wouldn't have felt the freedom and actual joy at moving my body "outside the box" of whatever pose was on the table -- but now, if you say "child's pose" (for example), and I feel like massaging my head while there or stretching hips back and forth, or enjoying namaste shark fin instead of active arms, etc,  I know it's ok, and it feels so great to honor what my body needs.  You give us permission to do what we need to do -- and that is a priceless gift -- so thank you <3

I remember the time when I was incredibly stressed and stiff and didn't know how to relax.
My family and friends recommended me to do yoga but I didn't believe in it.
Instead I used to have prejudices that kept me from trying it out.
I found that it was strange.

Eventually, when things went really bad, I joined  a public class and tried to let go. 
I had to get used to it but then I started to enjoy going to yoga classes.
In shavasana I learned to relax completely which was something I wasn't familiar with. 
It was pretty fascinating though I realised that going to a public yoga class once a week wasn't 100% what my body and soul needed.
So I browsed through YouTube and found your channel.

The more I let go the more things started to change.
To be honest, it was the best thing to happen to me.
I was amazed by all the new sensations I felt and even my mindset changed.
Now, I am more relaxed and I can better deal with anxiety.
I approach people and situation in a different manner.
I've become more gentle and kind.
It feels like yoga has brought out my good sides more.
In the past, I hadn't realised how shallow my breath was so that I was quite shocked by how good breathing feels now.
In addition, my body and posture have changed.
I've become stronger and more toned and flexible.

I'd haver never expect that I'd do yoga every day.
The more I practice yoga...
...the stronger I become
...the more I learn
...the more I find myself
...the deeper I breath
...the more I open up
...the better I can let go
...the more I can serve others
...the more confident I become
...the better I feel
...the more I grow

I experienced so much resistance this morning to practice day 4.
I felt/thought things like: "mehh...this session is too slow..", "meh...I'm gonna do something else...", "I am stupid for having so much resistance...".

At some point, I just played day 4, but just gazing at it feeling no good Juju, no Mambo, no Mojo, no nothing.

But at some moment I started to accept the moment. Accept the lack of motivation.
 That opened up the situation. And then I felt like:"hmm...maybe this IS what I need".

Played day 4 from the start. And actually experienced one of the nicest sessions ever...

I realize yoga for me was way too much about stretching. This session made me experience the importance of awareness, concious slow movements. 
I also felt emotions of loneliness and even cried a while. 
But I feel better, more at ease now.

I always wake up with a mindset of "you must do something!". But there isn't awareness in that.
Being more aware is where the magic happens.

Yesterday, I took the day off (day four) and watched tv, sat on the couch. Today I am picking up where I left off. I felt very frustrated coming ack to the mat today. It feels as though I'm starting from square one again. I've realized, that no matter how long my streak is, if I take a break from yoga, it will always feel like the first time at the beginning. And saying that/seeing that out loud is connecting dots to other parts of my life. Wanted to share with the community my recent discovery concerning food. Despite doing yoga daily with Adriene for almost a year, I wasn't feeling as good as I'd like or getting the weight loss, and overall health improvements I was hoping for. Three and a half years ago, I started having a smoothie for breakfast every day, and one of the recommended ingredients was peanut butter. After doing some research, I discovered peanut butter is one of the worst possible foods we can eat, and many people have peanut/peanut butter sensitivities without realizing. I cut out the PB, and since then I feel better, have more energy on and off the mat, am losing weight, and best of all, my overall health seems so much better. If you eat PB, especially daily, and are struggling, please go a week or two without the PB and see if it doesn't make a world of difference in your life.

Last summer, I turned 50, let go of myself for a while and by the holidays, I had gained 20 pounds. I cringed when I got on that scale so I asked for a Fitbit for Christmas, tweaked my nutrition, stumbled across Revolution and immediately subscribed. I have done yoga and dance, on and off in the past 20 years, so I was excited to embrace this commitment in my home. 
I began this Revolution series on day one. Day one was a gentle reminder to movements, day two and three gave me awareness of my neglected muscles that were being engaged with a mild soreness that was better each morning. Today, as I was into the routine for about 5 minutes, I felt like crying. Not from body pain or frustration, but more of a "I'm doing something really good for myself" realization. Of course, after a few seconds, that sensation had to pass so I could refocus and continue on the movements. But that was a joy-moment that I only experienced one other time when dancing. 
Your teaching is clear and well explained. I look forward to each morning's adventure and can't wait to see the better me at the end of this month! Thank you for helping all of us!

Thank you for teaching us not only yoga asana, but also other aspects of yoga. I really enjoyed learning more about prana today.
